# --- mark zero-volume rows (if any) ---
mask_zero = stock_name['Volume'] == 0

VERBOSE = False  # set to True only when debugging

print(f"Number of zero-volume rows: {mask_zero.sum()}")

if VERBOSE and mask_zero.any():
    display(stock_name.loc[mask_zero, ['Date', 'Volume']])


# Only do the rest if there ARE zeros
if mask_zero.any():
    # Replace 0 with NaN
    stock_name['Volume'] = stock_name['Volume'].replace(0, np.nan)

    # Set index to Date for time interpolation
    stock_name = stock_name.set_index('Date')

    # Interpolate
    stock_name['Volume'] = stock_name['Volume'].interpolate(method='time')

    # Back to integer + restore Date column
    stock_name['Volume'] = stock_name['Volume'].round().astype(int)
    stock_name = stock_name.reset_index()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def plot_financial_data(df, title):

    fig = px.line(title=title)

    # 1) Choose x-axis:
    #    - If a Date column exists, use it
    #    - Otherwise use the index (common for yfinance OHLC data)
    if 'Date' in df.columns:
        x = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
        cols_to_plot = [c for c in df.columns if c != 'Date']
    else:
        x = df.index
        cols_to_plot = list(df.columns)

    # 2) Add lines
    for col in cols_to_plot:
        fig.add_scatter(
            x=x,
            y=df[col],
            name=col,
            line=dict(width=5)
        )

    fig.update_layout(plot_bgcolor="white")
    fig.show()

# Defining a function that classifies the returns based on the magnitude

def percentage_return_classifier(percentage_return):
    
    if percentage_return > -0.3 and percentage_return <= 0.3:
        return 'Insignificant Change'
    elif percentage_return > 0.3 and percentage_return <= 3:
        return 'Positive Change'
    elif percentage_return > -3 and percentage_return <= -0.3:
        return 'Negative Change'
    elif percentage_return > 3 and percentage_return <= 7:
        return 'Large Positive Change'
    elif percentage_return > -7 and percentage_return <= -3:
        return 'Large Negative Change'
    elif percentage_return > 7:
        return 'Bull Run'
    elif percentage_return <= -7:
        return 'Bear Sell Off'

# Function to scale stock prices based on their initial starting price
# The objective of this function is to set all prices to start at a value of 1 
def price_scaling(raw_prices_df):
    scaled = raw_prices_df.copy()
    
    for col in scaled.columns[1:]:
        first_valid_price = scaled[col].dropna().iloc[0]
        scaled[col] = scaled[col] / first_valid_price

    return scaled

# Creating an array that holds random portfolio weights
import random

def generate_portfolio_weights(n):
    weights = []
    for i in range(n):
        weights.append(random.random())

    # Making the sum of all weights add up to 1
    weights = weights/np.sum(weights)
    return weights

import numpy as np

def asset_allocation(df, weights, initial_investment):
    """
    df: DataFrame with columns ['Date', stock1, stock2, ...]
    weights: array-like, must sum to 1
    initial_investment: float
    """

    # Defensive copy
    portfolio_df = df.copy()

    # Scaling prices so each stock starts at 1
    scaled_df = price_scaling(df)

    # Allocating capital to each stock
    for i, stock in enumerate(scaled_df.columns[1:]):
        portfolio_df[stock] = scaled_df[stock] * weights[i] * initial_investment

    # Total portfolio value (exclude Date)
    portfolio_df['Portfolio Value [$]'] = portfolio_df.iloc[:, 1:].sum(axis=1)

    # Daily percentage return
    portfolio_df['Portfolio Daily Return [%]'] = (
        portfolio_df['Portfolio Value [$]']
        .pct_change()
        .fillna(0) * 100
    )

    return portfolio_df

In[40]:
def simulation_engine(weights, initial_investment):
    # Performing asset allocation using the random weights (sent as arguments to the function)
    portfolio_df = asset_allocation(stock_prices, weights, initial_investment)
  
    # Return on investment is calculated using the last final value of the portfolio compared to its initial value
    return_on_investment = ((portfolio_df['Portfolio Value [$]'][-1:] - 
                             portfolio_df['Portfolio Value [$]'][0])/ 
                             portfolio_df['Portfolio Value [$]'][0]) * 100
  
    # Daily change of every stock in the portfolio 
    portfolio_daily_return_df = portfolio_df.drop(columns = ['Date', 'Portfolio Value [$]', 'Portfolio Daily Return [%]'])
    portfolio_daily_return_df = portfolio_daily_return_df.pct_change(1) 
  
    # Portfolio Expected Return formula
    expected_portfolio_return = np.sum(weights * portfolio_daily_return_df.mean() ) * 252
  
    covariance = portfolio_daily_return_df.cov() * 252 
    expected_volatility = np.sqrt(np.dot(weights.T, np.dot(covariance, weights)))

    # Checking out the chart for the 10-years U.S. treasury at https://ycharts.com/indicators/10_year_treasury_rate
    rf = 0.0415
    
    # Calculating Sharpe ratio
    sharpe_ratio = (expected_portfolio_return - rf)/expected_volatility 
    return expected_portfolio_return, expected_volatility, sharpe_ratio, portfolio_df['Portfolio Value [$]'][-1:].values[0], return_on_investment.values[0]

# Setting the number of simulation runs
sim_runs = 10000
initial_investment = 1000000

# Placeholder to store all weights
weights_runs = np.zeros((sim_runs, n))

# Placeholder to store all Sharpe ratios
sharpe_ratio_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)

# Placeholder to store all expected returns
expected_portfolio_returns_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)

# Placeholder to store all volatility values
volatility_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)

# Placeholder to store all returns on investment
return_on_investment_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)

# Placeholder to store all final portfolio values
final_value_runs = np.zeros(sim_runs)

for i in range(sim_runs):
    # Generating random weights 
    weights = generate_portfolio_weights(n)
    # Storing the weights
    weights_runs[i,:] = weights
    
    # Calling "simulation_engine" function and store Sharpe ratio, return and volatility
    # Asset allocation is performed using the "asset_allocation" function  
    expected_portfolio_returns_runs[i], volatility_runs[i], sharpe_ratio_runs[i], final_value_runs[i], return_on_investment_runs[i] = simulation_engine(weights, initial_investment)
